Chapter 1
Cohren
<s>4:30 a.m., Itania time. Cohren hated waking up so early. Especially because it was his responsibility to wake up all the other members of his company. Silently emerging from his bed, he put on his combat uniform, wore his tactical vest, and gathered the items from his locker, paying particular attention to a small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook attached to his belt. The helmet was fully equipped: respirator, goggles, everything necessary. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly stepped out of the barrack, the sound of squelching mud and crushed ice resounding under his boots.
He pulled a lighter from the pocket of his vest and a cigarette from the other. As he lit it, he took a small drag before opening the door slowly. Last week, he had had to be creative to wake the men and women under his command. He had stopped using the pre-set alarm clock, which only worked half the time because whatever came out of the speakers was just a faint whistle.
"Do you wake them?" Cohren turned to see Second Lieutenant Nemic arrive, walking.
"Ouep," responded Cohren.
"What are you planning to use this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and other soldiers rushed out, already dressed and equipped.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"Well, first off, we didn't want to see what you had planned to wake us up today. Secondly, the first shock troops up are the first to breakfast." One of them, Ravik, replied: "And you know how bad it can be."
"You make a point, Specialist," said Cohren. He reached out and flipped a switch. An alarm blared inside the barracks, loud and shrill. He heard commotion and chatter inside.
"Blow it out your ass, Valturi," exclaimed Nemic. "We could have thought they would have learned to wake up at the same time as you by now."
"Well, my training camp buddies here did it," Cohren turned towards Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "But again, their squad and section leaders know how to wake up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company streamed out in a mass. All had what they needed, from personal belongings to necessary equipment. Some of the new recruits seemed disoriented, others more frustrated.
"Good morning everyone," said Cohren cheerfully.
"With due respect, sir, why do you insist on waking us up this way?" asked one of the shock troopers, a corporal.
"Because the standard alarms are crap. And because Daybreak doesn't hit the snooze button," replied Cohren.
"Make sure you have all your personal effects," he continued. As the first lieutenant and assistant to the commander, it was his responsibility to oversee and assist the company alongside the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and second lieutenants, I'll give you and your units fifty minutes to conduct final checks and gather rations for the day."
The members of Company Exodus dispersed. They were part of the second division of the shock troopers, second army. Initially, they were separated into two distinct companies, Cohort and Dragger, before being reunited. This was a splinter company, and Cohren wasn't sure how to feel about his promotion to first lieutenant, primarily for reasons that motivated him.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first platoon, walked together under the light of the many lighting fixtures at the forward operating base, powered by generators. Most were tinted red to hide them from enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel assaults, both in the air and on the ground, to combat them.
"New day, new mission for the pioneers of hell," began Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"An advanced forward operating base outside Itania. We've been sent to support the ground assault," replied Cohren, taking a drag on his cigarette. Part of him blamed Craith for initiating him with cigarettes, but a year of combat changes a man, and he fell silent.
"Shit. The situation is deteriorating on the front," muttered Nemic. "All the news coming from there is 'Contribute to the war effort. Send help to the front of Kurgan.' Why not send help to the front of Howland?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, flicking his butt into the mud. "Anyway, we're going with the first tank platoon, so we won't have to march. Captain Shaw should be here."
"Did Shaw get us a transport?" asked Nemic, a bit surprised.
"Yes. Honestly, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not exceptional, but he's not unbearable."
Cohren placed his thumb and index finger on his throat mic while adjusting his backpack. "To all units of Company Exodus, assemble at the western vehicle park once you're done. We leave with the first tank platoon at 5:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squadron leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik had all been junior NCOs when they arrived here. All four were very good friends since their initial training on Earth. It seemed like such a long time ago even though it couldn't be more than two years. They were then squadron leaders. But Craith now commanded the second platoon since last week, after the demobilization of the previous captain, who had been wounded by a Daybreak sniper.
As they walked towards the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic saw a group of about eight main battle tanks Kronos and four Strykers. Their crews were busily ensuring that their war machines were ready for departure. Cohren quickly spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking with the tank platoon commander. As they approached, Shaw turned and walked towards them, his usually cold face showing no emotion.
"Lieutenant Nemic... Lieutenant Valturi..." He said that Cohren was slower, looking at Cohren's pistol holster before looking at them again. "I suppose the company is ready."
